{
  "Fluid Pressure and Force": "",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "",
  "What is the hydrostatic force on a rectangular plate 3 ft wide submerged vertically with its top edge at the water surface and its bottom edge at 5 ft depth?": "",
  "F = 62.4 * integral from 0 to 5 of 3h dh = 62.4 * 3 * [h^2/2] from 0 to 5 = 187.2 * 12.5 = 2340 lb.": "",
  "What is 'hydrostatic pressure'?": "",
  "Hydrostatic pressure is the pressure exerted by a fluid at rest due to gravity. At a depth h below the surface, the hydrostatic pressure is P = rho*g*h (or P = w*h where w is weight density). It increases linearly with depth.": "",
  "What is 'pressure' in physics?": "",
  "Pressure is defined as force per unit area: P = F/A. Its SI unit is the pascal (Pa), where 1 Pa = 1 N/m^2. In fluid mechanics, pressure at a point acts equally in all directions.": "",
  "What is the 'centroid' of a submerged plate and why is it relevant to fluid force?": "",
  "The centroid is the geometric center of the plate. For a flat plate submerged in a fluid, the total hydrostatic force equals the pressure at the centroid multiplied by the plate's area: F = (w * h_centroid) * A. This is a useful shortcut for uniform-density fluids.": "",
  "What is a 'pascal' as a unit of pressure?": "",
  "A pascal (Pa) is the SI unit of pressure, defined as one newton per square meter (1 Pa = 1 N/m^2). Standard atmospheric pressure is approximately 101,325 Pa.": "",
  "A rectangular swimming pool is 10 m long, 4 m wide, and 3 m deep. What is the hydrostatic force on one of the 10 m by 3 m walls? (Use water weight density = 9800 N/m^3.)": "",
  "F = 9800 * integral from 0 to 3 of 10*h dh = 98,000 * [h^2/2] from 0 to 3 = 98,000 * 4.5 = 441,000 N.": "",
  "A triangular gate in a dam has its vertex at the water surface and base of 8 ft at a depth of 6 ft. What is the hydrostatic force on the gate? (w = 62.4 lb/ft^3)": "",
  "The width at depth h is (8/6)*h = 4h/3 (by similar triangles, 0 at vertex/surface, 8 at depth 6). F = 62.4 * integral from 0 to 6 of h*(4h/3) dh = 62.4*(4/3) * integral from 0 to 6 of h^2 dh = 83.2 * [h^3/3] from 0 to 6 = 83.2 * 72 = 5990.4 lb.": "",
  "A vertical plate in the shape of a semicircle of radius 2 m is submerged in oil (weight density 7840 N/m^3) with its diameter at the surface. What is the hydrostatic force on the plate?": "",
  "At depth h, the width of the semicircle is 2*sqrt(r^2 - h^2) = 2*sqrt(4 - h^2). The force = 7840 * integral from 0 to 2 of h * 2*sqrt(4 - h^2) dh. Using substitution u = 4 - h^2, this integral evaluates to 7840*(2/3)(4)^(3/2) = 7840*16/3.": "",
  "A submarine's circular porthole has a diameter of 0.5 m and its center is 200 m below the ocean surface. If seawater has weight density 10,050 N/m^3, what is the hydrostatic force on the porthole?": "",
  "F = pressure at centroid * area = (10,050 * 200) * (pi * 0.25^2) = 2,010,000 * pi * 0.0625 = 2,010,000 * 0.19635 = 394,600 N (approximately). The centroid is at the center of the circle, 200 m deep.": "",
  "A water trough has a semicircular cross-section with radius 1 ft. When filled to the top, what is the hydrostatic force on one flat end? (w = 62.4 lb/ft^3)": "",
  "With diameter at the top (surface), at depth h, the width is 2*sqrt(1 - h^2). F = 62.4 * integral from 0 to 1 of h * 2*sqrt(1 - h^2) dh. Let u = 1 - h^2, du = -2h dh. F = 62.4 * integral from 1 to 0 of -sqrt(u) du = 62.4 * [2u^(3/2)/3] from 0 to 1 = 62.4 * 2/3 = 41.6 lb.": "",
  "A tank shaped like an inverted triangle (vertex at bottom) is 6 m wide at the top and 4 m deep. It is filled with a chemical solution of weight density 12,000 N/m^3. What is the force on one triangular end?": "",
  "At depth h from the surface, the width = 6(1 - h/4) = 6(4-h)/4 = 3(4-h)/2. F = 12,000 * integral from 0 to 4 of h * 3(4-h)/2 dh = 18,000 * integral from 0 to 4 of (4h - h^2) dh = 18,000 * [2h^2 - h^3/3] from 0 to 4 = 18,000 * (32 - 64/3) = 18,000 * (96/3 - 64/3) = 18,000 * 32/3 = 192,000 N. Let me recheck: 18000*(32/3) = 192,000. Hmm -- checking the width function: top is h=0, width=6. Bottom is h=4, width=0. So width = 6*(4-h)/4 = 3(4-h)/2. F = 12000 * integral of h*(3(4-h)/2) dh = 12000*(3/2)*integral of (4h-h^2)dh from 0 to 4 = 18000*[2h^2 - h^3/3] from 0 to 4 = 18000*(32-64/3) = 18000*(32/3) = 192,000 N. So the answer is 192,000 N. But that matches option C. Let me verify: F = 12000*integral from 0 to 4 of h * (3(4-h)/2) dh. The coefficient is 12000*3/2 = 18000. Integral of (4h-h^2) from 0 to 4 = [2h^2-h^3/3] from 0 to 4 = 32-64/3 = (96-64)/3 = 32/3. So F = 18000*(32/3) = 192,000 N. The correct answer should be 192,000.": "",
  "An oil storage tank has a rectangular inspection hatch 0.5 m wide and 0.8 m tall on its side. The top of the hatch is 2 m below the oil surface (oil weight density = 8500 N/m^3). What is the force on the hatch?": "",
  "F = 8500 * integral from 2 to 2.8 of 0.5*h dh = 4250 * [h^2/2] from 2 to 2.8 = 4250 * (3.92 - 2) = 4250 * 1.92 = 8,160 N. Alternatively, F = pressure at centroid * area = 8500 * 2.4 * (0.5 * 0.8) = 8500 * 2.4 * 0.4 = 8,160 N.": ""
}